UPI (Unified Payments Interface) fraud has become one of the most common forms of cybercrime in India, especially with the rapid
increase in digital transactions. It involves deceiving users into sharing sensitive information such as OTPs, UPI PINs, or 
unknowingly authorizing fraudulent payment requests.
A typical UPI fraud begins when a scammer contacts the victim through a phone call, SMS, or social media platform, pretending to
be a bank official, customer support executive, or even a trusted acquaintance. The scammer creates a sense of urgency by claiming
that there is a problem with the victim’s bank account, or by offering fake rewards, cashback, or job opportunities. The victim is 
then asked to share their OTP or UPI PIN, or is tricked into accepting a “collect request” on their UPI application.
In many cases, the victim believes they are receiving money, but instead ends up authorizing a payment. Once the transaction is 
approved,the money is instantly transferred to the scammer’s account. Due to the real-time nature of UPI transactions, recovering
the lost money becomes extremely difficult.
Students and young individuals are particularly vulnerable targets due to their frequent use of digital payment platforms and
lack of awareness about such scams. The consequences include financial loss, mental stress, and loss of trust in digital systems.
Therefore, spreading awareness and adopting safe online practices is essential to prevent such cybercrimes.
